  "text": "# Chromium Renderer Process Sandbox Audit\n\n## 1. Linux seccomp-BPF Base Policy\n\nThe fundamental sandbox implementation for Linux is found in **sandbox/policy/linux/bpf_base_policy_linux.h** and **bpf_base_policy_linux.cc**. The class `BPFBasePolicy` (namespace: `sandbox::policy`) implements the seccomp-BPF base policy that reduces the Linux kernel's attack surface. This class inherits from `bpf_dsl::Policy` and serves as the baseline for all other Linux seccomp-BPF policies. Key methods include:\n- `EvaluateSyscall(int system_call_number)`: Evaluates syscall restrictions\n- `InvalidSyscall()`: Handles invalid syscalls\n- `GetFSDeniedErrno()`: Returns errno for filesystem access denials\n\nThe implementation uses `BaselinePolicy` (from **sandbox/linux/seccomp-bpf-helpers/baseline_policy.h**) as the underlying policy mechanism.\n\n## 2. Windows Sandbox Policy Configuration\n\nThe Windows sandbox policy is defined in **sandbox/win/src/sandbox_policy.h**. The core `TargetPolicy` class (namespace: `sandbox`) serves as the abstract interface for configuring Windows sandbox policies for target processes. Related to this is the `TargetConfig` class which handles:\n- Token levels (initial and lockdown)\n- Job object security levels\n- File access permissions\n- DLL loading restrictions\n- Integrity levels\n- Process mitigations\n- App Container profiles\n\nThe actual implementation uses policy objects that inherit from these interfaces and are created via `BrokerServices::CreatePolicy()`.\n\n## 3. Renderer Process Sandbox Configuration\n\nThe renderer process sandbox parameters are configured through **content/browser/renderer_host/renderer_sandboxed_process_launcher_delegate.h** and **renderer_sandboxed_process_launcher_delegate.cc**.\n\nThe `RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegate` class (namespace: `content`) implements:\n- `GetSandboxType()`: Returns `sandbox::mojom::Sandbox::kRenderer`\n- Platform-specific implementations for Windows (`RendererSandboxedProcessLauncherDelegateWin`) with:\n  - `GetSandboxTag()`: Returns sandbox tag (\"renderer-pdfium\" for PDF renderers)\n  - `InitializeConfig(sandbox::TargetConfig* config)`: Configures TargetConfig policies\n  - `PostSpawnTarget()`: Post-launch process configuration\n  - `CetCompatible()`: Controls Control Flow Guard compatibility\n\nOn Linux/ChromeOS, renderer sandboxing uses the zygote process via `GetZygote()` and applies `RendererProcessPolicy` which extends `BPFBasePolicy`.\n\n## 4. SandboxType Enum and Profile Mappings\n\nThe `Sandbox` enum is defined in **sandbox/policy/mojom/sandbox.mojom** (namespace: `sandbox::mojom`) and includes values:\n- `kRenderer`: Hosts untrustworthy web content with maximum OS access restrictions\n- `kGpu`: GPU service access to GPU drivers\n- `kUtility`: Generic utilities with limited system service access\n- `kService`: Computation-only services\n- `kAudio`, `kNetwork`, `kCdm`, and platform-specific types\n\nPolicy helper functions in **sandbox/policy/sandbox_type.h** include:\n- `IsUnsandboxedSandboxType(sandbox::mojom::Sandbox)`: Checks if sandbox is disabled\n- `SetCommandLineFlagsForSandboxType()`: Configures command-line switches\n- `SandboxTypeFromCommandLine()`: Parses sandbox type from command-line\n- `StringFromUtilitySandboxType()` / `UtilitySandboxTypeFromString()`: String conversions\n\nPlatform-specific sandbox mappings are implemented in:\n- **sandbox/policy/linux/sandbox_linux.h** and **sandbox_linux.cc**: Maps sandbox types to seccomp-BPF policies\n- **sandbox/policy/win/sandbox_win.h**: Maps sandbox types to Windows token/job configurations  \n- **sandbox/policy/mac/sandbox_mac.h**: Maps sandbox types to macOS sandbox profiles\n\nThe Linux implementation uses policy builders that select appropriate policies (e.g., `RendererProcessPolicy` for `kRenderer`, `GpuProcessPolicy` for `kGpu`) based on the `Sandbox` type, while the Windows implementation uses `SandboxWin::GetPolicyForSandboxType()` to configure token levels and job restrictions."
}

